<subSubSection lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="519" pageId="7" pageNumber="518" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1436,1916,2013]" box="[151,699,1916,1941]" pageId="7" pageNumber="518">
<heading bold="true" box="[151,699,1916,1941]" fontSize="10" level="2" pageId="7" pageNumber="518" reason="2">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,699,1916,1941]" pageId="7" pageNumber="518">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kiesenwetter" authorityYear="1874" box="[151,348,1916,1940]" class="Insecta" family="Scirtidae" genus="Scirtes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="518" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="japonicus">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,348,1916,1940]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="518">Scirtes japonicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species group (
<bibRefCitation author="Nyholm" box="[530,691,1916,1941]" pageId="7" pageNumber="518" refString="Nyholm, T. (2002) Scirtes japonicus Kiesenwetter and its allies with descriptions of Scirtes ussuriensis n. sp. (Coleoptera Scirtidae). Entomologische Blatter, 98, 49 - 60." type="journal article" year="2002">Nyholm 2002</bibRefCitation>
)
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1436,1916,2013]" lastBlockId="8.[151,1437,151,789]" lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="519" pageId="7" pageNumber="518">
<bibRefCitation author="Nyholm" box="[199,382,1952,1977]" pageId="7" pageNumber="518" refString="Nyholm, T. (2002) Scirtes japonicus Kiesenwetter and its allies with descriptions of Scirtes ussuriensis n. sp. (Coleoptera Scirtidae). Entomologische Blatter, 98, 49 - 60." type="journal article" year="2002">Nyholm (2002)</bibRefCitation>
based this group primarily on the form of the penis: “symmetric with parameroids longitudinally deeply cleft and tegmen with a lateral lobe (paramere) on each side”. We would add: first segment of labial palpus shorter than second, mandible incisivus moderately long, caudal margin of metacoxal plate concave and caudal margin of sternite 7 moderately concave; larvae with tip of mandible bifid and maxillary palpus threesegmented (
<bibRefCitation author="Watts" box="[285,417,224,248]" pageId="8" pageNumber="519" refString="Watts, C. H. S. (2004) Revision of Australian Scirtes Illiger and Ora Clark (Coleoptera: Scirtidae). Transactions of the Royal Society of South Australia, 128, 131 - 168." type="journal article" year="2004">Watts 2004</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Yoshitomi" box="[430,613,223,248]" pageId="8" pageNumber="519" refString="Yoshitomi, H. (2005) Systematic revision of the family Scirtidae of Japan, with phylogeny, morphology and bionomics (Insecta: Coleoptera, Scirtoidea). Japanese Journal of systematic Entomology, Monographic Series, 3, 1 - 212. [Matsuyama]" type="journal article" year="2005">Yoshitomi 2005</bibRefCitation>
). The prehensors and bursal sclerites of all three Australian species (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 2 – 5" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1971,1994]" captionTargetBox="[224,1384,198,1920]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[191,1396,180,1994]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 2 – 5. Portion of female reproductive tract: a) bursa, b) prehensor, c) accessory gland, d) bursal sclerite. 2) Scirtes auratus; 3) S. kaytae; 4) S. tindaleensis; 5) S. emmaae." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1048633/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="519">Figs 3–5</figureCitation>
) are closely similar to those of 
<taxonomicName authority="(Yoshitomi 2005)" authorityName="Yoshitomi" authorityYear="2005" baseAuthorityName="Yoshitomi" baseAuthorityYear="2005" box="[547,891,260,285]" class="Insecta" family="Scirtidae" genus="Scirtes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="519" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="japonicus">
<emphasis box="[547,561,261,284]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="519">S</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[574,683,261,284]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="519">japonicus</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Yoshitomi" box="[698,883,260,285]" pageId="8" pageNumber="519" refString="Yoshitomi, H. (2005) Systematic revision of the family Scirtidae of Japan, with phylogeny, morphology and bionomics (Insecta: Coleoptera, Scirtoidea). Japanese Journal of systematic Entomology, Monographic Series, 3, 1 - 212. [Matsuyama]" type="journal article" year="2005">Yoshitomi 2005</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="519" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1437,151,789]" pageId="8" pageNumber="519">
The penis of no Australian species has this morphology. The aedeagus of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Watts" authorityYear="2004" box="[1054,1178,296,320]" class="Insecta" family="Scirtidae" genus="Scirtes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="519" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="emmaae">
<emphasis box="[1054,1178,296,320]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="519">S. emmaae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is simple and appears plesiomorphic as it conforms closely to the scirtid ground plan (
<bibRefCitation author="Zwick" box="[890,1033,332,357]" pageId="8" pageNumber="519" refString="Zwick, P. (2016) Australian Marsh Beetles (Coleoptera: Scirtidae). 9. The relations of Australian Ypsiloncyphon species to their Asian congeners, additions mainly to Petrocyphon and Prionocyphon, and a key to Australian genera of Scirtinae. Zootaxa, 4085 (2), 151 - 198. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4085.2.1" type="journal article" year="2016">Zwick 2016</bibRefCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Watts" authorityYear="2004" box="[1054,1212,332,357]" class="Insecta" family="Scirtidae" genus="Scirtes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="519" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="kaytae">
<emphasis box="[1054,1212,332,357]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="519">Scirtes kaytae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Watts" authorityYear="2004" box="[1272,1436,332,357]" class="Insecta" family="Scirtidae" genus="Scirtes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="519" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tindaleensis">
<emphasis box="[1272,1286,333,356]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="519">S</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1302,1436,332,357]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="519">tindaleensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have asymmetric aedeagi resembling those of species in the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Blackburn" authorityYear="1892" box="[826,927,367,392]" class="Insecta" family="Scirtidae" genus="Scirtes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="519" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="helmsi">
<emphasis box="[826,927,367,392]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="519">S. helmsi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1437,151,789]" pageId="8" pageNumber="519">
The aedeagus of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Watts" authorityYear="2004" box="[393,515,405,428]" class="Insecta" family="Scirtidae" genus="Scirtes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="519" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="emmaae">
<emphasis box="[393,515,405,428]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="519">S. emmaae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, particularly the apical triangular lobes of the parameres, is similar to those of 
<taxonomicName authority="Yoshitomi" authorityName="Yoshitomi" authorityYear="1851" class="Insecta" family="Scirtidae" genus="Scirtes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="519" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="micronesianus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="519">S. micronesianus</emphasis>
Yoshitomi
</taxonomicName>
, which was placed in a separate group by 
<bibRefCitation author="Yoshitomi" box="[997,1203,439,464]" pageId="8" pageNumber="519" refString="Yoshitomi, H. (2009) The Scirtes (Coleoptera: Scirtidae: Scirtinae) of Micronesia. Zootaxa, 1974, 1 - 16." type="journal article" year="2009">Yoshitomi (2009)</bibRefCitation>
and named the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Yoshitomi" authorityYear="1851" class="Insecta" family="Scirtidae" genus="Scirtes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="519" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="micronesianus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="519">S. micronesianus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group. However, other than their aedeagi, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Watts" authorityYear="2004" box="[836,963,477,500]" class="Insecta" family="Scirtidae" genus="Scirtes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="519" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="emmaae">
<emphasis box="[836,963,477,500]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="519">S. emmaae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Watts" authorityYear="2004" box="[1029,1137,476,501]" class="Insecta" family="Scirtidae" genus="Scirtes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="519" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="kaytae">
<emphasis box="[1029,1137,476,501]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="519">S. kaytae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are morphologically and genetically close and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Watts" authorityYear="2004" box="[391,552,511,536]" class="Insecta" family="Scirtidae" genus="Scirtes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="519" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tindaleensis">
<emphasis box="[391,552,511,536]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="519">S. tindaleensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is also close on both larval and adult morphology yet only 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Watts" authorityYear="2004" box="[1213,1334,512,536]" class="Insecta" family="Scirtidae" genus="Scirtes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="519" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="emmaae">
<emphasis box="[1213,1334,512,536]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="519">S. emmaae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
could be classified in the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Yoshitomi" authorityYear="1851" box="[342,535,549,572]" class="Insecta" family="Scirtidae" genus="Scirtes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="519" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="micronesianus">
<emphasis box="[342,535,549,572]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="519">S. micronesianus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group. We think that on this evidence these three species belong in the same species group and have placed all three Australian species in the 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Yoshitomi" baseAuthorityYear="2005" box="[898,1036,584,608]" class="Insecta" family="Scirtidae" genus="Scirtes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="519" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="japonicus">
<emphasis box="[898,1036,584,608]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="519">S. japonicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group based on sequence data and adult and larval morphology but recognise that future study is needed to confirm this placement, particularly in light of the conflicting morphology of the male genitalia.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="519" type="reference_group">
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1437,151,789]" pageId="8" pageNumber="519">
<taxonomicName authority="Ruta &amp; Yoshitomi, 2010" authorityName="Ruta &amp; Yoshitomi" authorityYear="2010" box="[199,697,692,717]" class="Insecta" family="Scirtidae" genus="Scirtes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="519" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nehouensis">
<emphasis box="[199,409,692,717]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="519">Scirtes nehouensis</emphasis>
Ruta &amp; Yoshitomi, 2010
</taxonomicName>
from New Caledonia appears to us on both general morphology and male and female genitalia (
<bibRefCitation author="Ruta" box="[509,797,727,752]" pageId="8" pageNumber="519" refString="Ruta, R. &amp; Yoshitomi, H. (2010 b) Scirtidae: The genus Scirtes Illiger (Coleoptera). In: Jach, M. A. &amp; Balke, M. (Eds.), Water Beetles of New Caledonia. Part 1. Monographs on Coleoptera 3. Natural History Museum, Wien, pp. 403 - 438." type="journal article" year="2010" yearSuffix="b">Ruta &amp; Yoshitomi 2010b</bibRefCitation>
) to be conspecific with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Watts" authorityYear="2004" box="[1073,1195,728,752]" class="Insecta" family="Scirtidae" genus="Scirtes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="519" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="emmaae">
<emphasis box="[1073,1195,728,752]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="519">S. emmaae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. We herein place the species in synonymy under 
<taxonomicName authority="Watts, 2004" authorityName="Watts" authorityYear="2004" box="[462,782,764,788]" class="Insecta" family="Scirtidae" genus="Scirtes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="519" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="emmaae">
<emphasis box="[462,639,765,788]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="519">Scirtes emmaae</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Watts" box="[645,782,764,788]" pageId="8" pageNumber="519" refString="Watts, C. H. S. (2004) Revision of Australian Scirtes Illiger and Ora Clark (Coleoptera: Scirtidae). Transactions of the Royal Society of South Australia, 128, 131 - 168." type="journal article" year="2004">Watts, 2004</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
